{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17500845","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17500845"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:18:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1686"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1686"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.78,0.05,0.02,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44107"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1686","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1686"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1686"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29084"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"892"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"11399"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11400"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44107","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/44107"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 19-year-old man presents with a limp and painful knee which developed during a game of football earlier in the day. On examination the knee is warm, swollen and an effusion is present. There is tenderness along the medial joint line. Full flexion is possible, but extension is limited to 40\u00b0. The posterior and anterior drawer signs are negative.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Lateral meniscus tear","Medial meniscus tear","Anterior cruciate rupture","Posterior cruciate rupture","Haemarthrosis"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EInjury of the knee joint meniscus is one of the most common injuries in the human body. The warmth and swelling suggest an inflammatory response and the point of tenderness indicates that this is a \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial meniscus tear.\u003C/strong\u003E The menisci of the knee have several important roles including shock absorption and load distribution, stability, nutrition for articular cartilage, limitation of flexion and extension and control of movement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeniscal tears occur due to a shear force between the femur and tibia, this is typically a twisting force on a weightbearing, flexed knee, or due to degeneration in older patients. Tears often present as severe pain along the joint-line, swelling as well as catching, clicking and locking of the knee. Diagnosis is clinical but MRI may be used to confirm the tear.\u00a0\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the knee is locked and joint function is lost, the patient should be referred for surgical intervention. Surgical management is also indicated in younger patients or older patients when conservative measures have failed. The risk of osteoarthritis is increased with dysfunctional meniscal structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll patients should be initially managed with conservative measures including rest, ice, compression and elevation of the affected limb. Longer term conservative measures include analgesia with nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) and physiotherapy.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Medial meniscus tears are one of the commonest knee injuries."],"references":["Shiraev T, Anderson S, Hope N. Meniscal tear Presentation, diagnosis and management. Australian Family Physician. 2012;41:182-7."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29084"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1686"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"29084","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/29084"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-04-07T08:57:06+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-04-07T08:57:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1686"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"44107"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"34","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/34"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Orthopaedics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"892","links":{"self":"https://